1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,450
That's basic to creative thinking.

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:07,010
Here are suggestions to help you develop creative power through belief.

3
00:00:07,010 --> 00:00:08,529
1.

4
00:00:08,960 --> 00:00:14,049
Eliminate the word impossible from your thinking and speaking vocabularies.

5
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:16,769
Impossible is a failure word.

6
00:00:16,960 --> 00:00:22,769
The thought it's impossible sets off a chain reaction of other thoughts to prove you're right.

7
00:00:22,769 --> 00:00:24,210
2.

8
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:28,049
Think of something you've been wanting to do but felt you couldn't.

9
00:00:28,160 --> 00:00:31,490
Now make a list of reasons why you can do it.

10
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:37,970
Many of us whip and defeat our desires simply because we concentrate on why we can't,

11
00:00:38,080 --> 00:00:42,850
when the only thing worthy of our mental concentration is why we can.

12
00:00:44,640 --> 00:00:50,370
Recently I read a newspaper item that said there are too many counties in most states.

13
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:57,570
The article pointed out that most county boundaries were established decades before the first automobile was built,

14
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:01,010
and while the horse and buggy was the chief mode of travel.

15
00:01:01,200 --> 00:01:09,250
But today, with fast automobiles and good roads, there is no reason why three or four counties could not be combined.

16
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:17,330
This would cut down greatly on duplicated services so that taxpayers would actually get better service for less money.

17
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:23,570
The writer of this article said he thought he had stumbled across a really live idea,

18
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:27,570
so he interviewed 30 people at random to get their reactions.

19
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:28,690
The result?

20
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:36,929
Not one person thought the idea had merit, even though it would provide them with better local government at less cost.

21
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:40,289
That's an example of traditional thinking.

22
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:43,490
The traditional thinker's mind is paralyzed.

23
00:01:43,680 --> 00:01:50,210
He reasons, it's been this way for a hundred years, therefore it must be good and must stay this way.

24
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:51,970
Why risk a change?

25
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:56,130
Average people have always resented progress.

26
00:01:56,400 --> 00:02:03,409
Many voiced a protest toward the automobile on the grounds that nature meant for us to walk or use horses.

27
00:02:03,680 --> 00:02:06,529
The airplane seemed drastic to many.

28
00:02:06,720 --> 00:02:11,409
Man had no right to enter the province reserved for birds.

29
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:17,730
A lot of status-quoers still insist that man has no business in space.

30
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:23,010
One top missile expert recently gave an answer to this kind of thinking.

31
00:02:23,360 --> 00:02:28,769
Man belongs, says Dr. Von Braun, where man wants to go.

32
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:36,850
Around 1900, a sales executive discovered a scientific principle of sales management.

33
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:41,330
It received a lot of publicity and even found its way into textbooks.

34
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:43,010
The principle was this.

35
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:46,529
There is one best way to sell a product.

36
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:50,450
Find the best way, then never deviate from it.

37
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:58,769
Fortunately for this man's company, new leadership came in in time to save the organization from financial ruin.

38
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:08,049
Contrast that experience with the philosophy of Crawford H. Greenwalt, president of one of the nation's largest business organizations,

39
00:03:08,240 --> 00:03:10,850
E. I. DuPont de Nemours.

40
00:03:11,200 --> 00:03:18,769
In a talk at Columbia University, Mr. Greenwalt said, There are many ways in which a good job can be done,

41
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:23,330
as many ways, in fact, as there are men to whom the task is given.

42
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:27,490
In truth, there is no one best way to do anything.

43
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:32,370
There is no one best way to decorate an apartment, landscape a lawn,

44
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:35,649
make a sail, rear a child, or cook a steak.

45
00:03:35,920 --> 00:03:39,970
There are as many best ways as there are creative minds.

46
00:03:40,640 --> 00:03:42,450
Nothing grows in ice.

47
00:03:42,640 --> 00:03:47,330
If we let tradition freeze our minds, new ideas can't sprout.

